Evolution of Pain (The Nightmare Scenario)

Imagine you build a global banking system.

You have databases in:

🇮🇳 India (DB-B)

🇺🇸 USA (DB-C)

Both databases replicate the same data.

Example:

Account Balance = 1000

Now a user in India withdraws:

Withdraw 200

New balance:

800

But suddenly…

💥 Network cable between India and USA breaks.

Now the databases cannot communicate.

But users are still sending requests.

Disaster begins

User in India sees:

Balance = 800

User in USA sees:

Balance = 1000

Now both withdraw money.

Result:

Double spending
Data corruption
Financial disaster

This exact problem is why CAP theorem exists.

CAP theorem says:

In a distributed system with replicated data, you cannot guarantee all three properties simultaneously.

The three properties are:

Property	Meaning
C	Consistency
A	Availability
P	Partition Tolerance
3️⃣ Understanding Each Property (Feynman Style)
1️⃣ Consistency (C)

All nodes return same data.

Example:

Write:

A = 5

Now if you read from any server, you must get:

A = 5

Never stale data.

2️⃣ Availability (A)

Every request gets a response.

Even if the response is:

Error
Timeout
Failure

But the system must reply.

Your notes describe this as:

Every request receives a response whether success or failure. 

HLD_Merged

3️⃣ Partition Tolerance (P)

Network failures will happen.

Example:

Server India ↔ Server USA

Network cable breaks.

Now both servers cannot talk.

But the system must still work.

Why We Can't Have All Three (CAP)

Imagine:

DB B (India)
DB C (USA)

Network breaks:

B  ❌  C

Now a write happens:

A = 6

But replication cannot happen.

So:

Node	Value
B	6
C	5

Now you must choose:

Option 1

Return stale data → Availability

Option 2

Reject request → Consistency

You cannot do both.
1️⃣ AP (Availability + Partition Tolerance)

1️⃣ Evolution of Pain (Why CAP Exists)
Nightmare Scenario: Network Breaks Between Servers

In a distributed system, data is stored on multiple servers.

Example:

Server A → India
Server B → US
Server C → Europe


Normally they sync data.

4

Now imagine the network breaks between regions.

India servers  ❌  US servers


This is called a Network Partition.

Now systems must choose:

1️⃣ Stop responding to users
or
2️⃣ Continue working with possibly inconsistent data


This trade-off leads to CAP theorem.

2️⃣ The Cure: AP Systems

AP = Availability + Partition Tolerance

Meaning:

System keeps working even if data is temporarily inconsistent.

4

AP systems prioritize:

Property	Meaning
Availability	System always responds
Partition tolerance	Survive network splits

They sacrifice strong consistency.

3️⃣ Core Mechanism (Feynman Explanation)

Imagine two database nodes:

Server A
Server B


User updates value.

Value = 5 → 6


If network partition happens:

Server A = 6
Server B = 5


Now reads depend on which server you hit.

Example:

User 1 → Server A → 6
User 2 → Server B → 5


System still works.

Later servers synchronize.

This is called:

Eventual Consistency


Meaning:

Data will become consistent eventually, not immediately.

4️⃣ Real-World Analogy

Think of two supermarket branches updating inventory.

Branch A sells item.

Stock = 10 → 9


But branch B hasn't received update yet.

Stock = 10


Customers see slightly different values.

But stores keep operating.

Later inventory syncs.

5️⃣ What If Sandbox (Trade-offs)
❓ What if system waited for consistency?

Then during partition:

System stops responding


Users see errors.

❓ What if system allowed inconsistent data?

System stays online.

But some users may see old data.

This is AP behavior.

❓ What happens after partition resolves?

Nodes synchronize.

Example:

Server A = 6
Server B = 5


Conflict resolution chooses correct value.

6️⃣ Systems That Use AP

These systems prefer availability over strict consistency.

Database	Type
Cassandra	AP
DynamoDB	AP
CouchDB	AP
Riak	AP
7️⃣ Good Use Cases

AP systems work best when temporary inconsistency is acceptable.

Examples:

System	Why AP works
Social media likes	Slight delay okay
Messaging systems	Messages sync later
Recommendation feeds	Minor inconsistencies acceptable
Large-scale analytics	Availability more important

2️⃣ CP (Consistency + Partition Tolerance)

Evolution of Pain (Why CP Systems Exist)
Nightmare Scenario: Wrong Data

Imagine a banking system with multiple servers.

Data replication:

Server A → India
Server B → US


Both hold the same account balance.

4

User balance:

Balance = $100


User withdraws:

Withdraw $70


Server A updates:

Balance = $30


But due to network partition:

Server B still shows $100


Another withdrawal happens.

💥 Result:

$70 + $70 withdrawn
Balance = -$40


The system broke financial correctness.

For banking systems this is unacceptable.

So engineers designed CP systems.

2️⃣ The Cure: CP Systems

CP = Consistency + Partition Tolerance

Meaning:

All nodes always return the same data
Even if network partitions happen


But the cost is Availability.

4

During partition:

System may stop responding


But it never returns incorrect data.

3️⃣ Core Mechanism (Feynman Explanation)

In CP systems, updates require agreement between nodes.

Example:

Server A
Server B
Server C


Write request:

Set value = 6


Process:

A → propose update
B → approve
C → approve


Only after majority agreement the value changes.

Example:

A = 6
B = 6
C = 6


If network partition happens:

A isolated
B ↔ C connected


Then only majority side continues.

Minority node stops responding.

This ensures strong consistency.

4️⃣ Real-World Analogy

Think of three bank managers approving transactions.

Transaction rule:

Majority must approve


Scenario:

Manager A unreachable
Manager B + Manager C available


Transaction proceeds.

But if only one manager available:

Transaction rejected


Correctness is preserved.

5️⃣ What If Sandbox (Trade-offs)
❓ What if system prioritized availability instead?

Then we could get:

Different balances on different servers


Banking disaster.

❓ What if majority nodes are unavailable?

Then system stops responding.

Example:

3 node cluster
2 nodes down


Writes rejected.

❓ Why do CP systems use leader election?

To maintain order.

One node becomes:

Leader


All writes go through the leader.

Protocols used:

Raft

Paxos

Zookeeper consensus

6️⃣ Systems That Use CP
System	Type
HBase	CP
MongoDB (majority writes)	CP
Zookeeper	CP
etcd	CP

These systems ensure strong consistency.

7️⃣ Good Use Cases

CP systems are used when correctness is critical.

Examples:

System	Why CP
Banking	balances must be exact
Payment systems	no duplicate transactions
Inventory systems	avoid overselling
Distributed locks	avoid conflicts

8️⃣ CA 

1️⃣ Evolution of Pain (Before Distributed Systems)

Originally many systems ran on one single database server.

Architecture:

Users → Application Server → Database

4

Because there is only one database, two properties are guaranteed:

Property	Meaning
Consistency	Every read returns the latest data
Availability	Database always responds

Example:

Balance = 100
Withdraw 20
Balance = 80


Every user sees 80 immediately.

No conflicting data.

2️⃣ The Cure: CA Systems

CA = Consistency + Availability

Meaning:

System always responds
AND
Data is always correct


But this only works when there is no network partition.

Because CA systems assume:

All components can communicate

4
3️⃣ Core Mechanism (Feynman Explanation)

In CA systems:

Single source of truth


Example:

Database → MySQL


All clients read/write from the same database.

Flow:

Client → Server → Database


Since there is only one database, data stays consistent.

And server always responds.

4️⃣ The Big Limitation

CA systems cannot handle network partitions.

Example:

Server A ❌ cannot reach Server B


Now system must choose:

Consistency
OR
Availability


CAP theorem says:

When partition happens, you cannot keep both.

So pure CA systems only work in non-distributed environments.

5️⃣ Real-World Analogy

Think of a single cashier at a shop.

One register
One record book


Every transaction updates the same book.

Result:

Data always correct
Always available


But if the cashier disappears:

Shop stops operating


No redundancy.

6️⃣ What If Sandbox
❓ What if we replicate CA systems across servers?

Now network partitions can occur.

Then system must choose:

CP or AP


CA is no longer possible.

❓ Why do large distributed systems rarely choose CA?

Because networks always experience partitions.

Example:

region outages

network latency

cable failures

So real distributed systems choose:

CP or AP

7️⃣ Systems That Behave Like CA

These are typically single-node or tightly coupled systems.

Examples:

System	Why
MySQL (single instance)	centralized
PostgreSQL (single node)	centralized
Oracle DB	centralized deployments
Traditional monolithic apps	single DB
8️⃣ CAP Comparison (Full Picture)
Type	Guarantees	Sacrifice
CA	Consistency + Availability	Partition tolerance
CP	Consistency + Partition tolerance	Availability
AP	Availability + Partition tolerance	Consistency